usage: caseproc [-h] [--config FILE] [--error] [--update] [--rename OLD NEW]
                [--restate LABEL STATEMENT] [--ltac FILENAME]
                [--validate | --select SELECTOR | --stdout | --selftest]
                [files ...]

Process assurance case LTAC file and update documentation files (Markdown/HTML)

positional arguments:
  files                 Documentation file(s) (Markdown/HTML) to update in
                        place (default: auto-discover case.md etc.)

options:
  -h, --help            show this help message and exit
  --config FILE         path to a JSON file containing configuration key/value
                        pairs
  --error               treat warnings as errors (non-zero exit on any
                        warning)
  --update              update the LTAC file to synchronize citation
                        statements with their declarations
  --rename OLD NEW      rename identifier OLD to NEW in LTAC and document
                        files
  --restate LABEL STATEMENT
                        update the statement for LABEL in LTAC and document
                        files
  --ltac FILENAME, -l FILENAME
                        LTAC file to load (default: case.ltac or
                        docs/case.ltac)
  --validate            validate and report warnings/errors; do not produce
                        output
  --select SELECTOR, -s SELECTOR
                        render SELECTOR to stdout and exit (see selector table
                        below)
  --stdout              process document files and write concatenated result
                        to stdout
  --selftest            run the built-in doctest suite and exit (0 = all pass,
                        1 = any fail)

This program normally reads an LTAC file and then updates (modifies)
document file(s) in Markdown/HTML to update them: their headers that involve
assurance case elements or packages, their HTML anchors, and all text regions
inside the markers <!-- caseproc SELECTOR --> ... <!-- end caseproc -->.

The intended normal use is that you simply edit the LTAC file for the
high-level argument and the document file(s) in Markdown/HTML for all details
(the "content" in SACM parlance). Then run this program to validate the
structure and update your document files in Markdown/HTML with graphics,
hyperlinks, and other material.

By default the program treats the LTAC file strictly as an input and
it will *not* modify the LTAC file. However, the options --update,
--rename, and --restate *do* modify the LTAC file.
All file updates are done carefully. The updated files are generated
first as temporary files, then the originals are moved to .backup/,
and only then are the generated files moved to their final destinations.
If you don't want to perform an in-place update of the files, use --stdout.

Selectors are of format `KIND [ID | *]`, where KIND is:
  ltac/markdown  ID|*   render as an indented Markdown bullet list
  ltac/html      ID|*   render as a nested HTML list
  sacm/mermaid   ID|*   render as a SACM Mermaid flowchart
  gsn/mermaid    ID|*   render as a GSN Mermaid flowchart
  statement      ID     one-line statement for an element
  references     ID     Markdown links to packages that reference the element
  info           ID     statement followed by references
Omit ID to use the element set by the nearest preceding header (filter mode).
Use * to render all packages (ltac/*, sacm/mermaid, and gsn/mermaid only).

Validations on the LTAC file (always):
  - There must be no circularities (this prevents circular reasoning)
  - All elements must be reachable from the first node of the first package
  - Claim/Strategy must not appear under Evidence, Context, or Assumption
  - Each identifier must be declared (no ^ prefix) exactly once
  - Citing identifiers (^ID) must have a matching declaration
  - In citations naming a package (^[PkgName] ID) the package must declare ID
  - Element type must be consistent across all uses of the same identifier
  - Statement text must be consistent across all uses of the same identifier
    (use --update to make LTAC statements consistent with their declaration)
  - Each element must carry at *most* one assertion status option
    (needsSupport, axiomatic, defeated, assumed); see SACM spec section 11
  - All generated anchor names (e.g., "claim-x-is-secure") must be unique

Additional checks when document files are provided:
  - Headers matching "TYPE ID" or "TYPE ID: statement" are cross-checked, and
    they must not have an unknown ID (one not in the LTAC).
    By default headers' statements are updated, but if update_headers is false,
    each statement much match its LTAC definition's statement.
  - Every declared LTAC element must have a corresponding document header
    (as this is where the additional information about it can be placed).

Configuration keys (--config FILE, JSON object):
  base_url           base URL for hyperlinks in sacm/mermaid and gsn/mermaid output (default: "")
  markdown_base_url  base URL for hyperlinks in ltac/markdown and ltac/html output (default: "")
  pkg_label          word used to identify packages in headers and output (default: "Package ")
  pkg_header_prefix  string prepended to each package header when rendering * (default: "### ")
  pkg_header_suffix  string appended after each package header when rendering * (default: newline)
  update_headers     if true, rewrite stale headers instead of warning (default: false)

For full details see docs/design-spec.md.
